{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783301881,"nonce":"c7Q6b/jafGhPqw7qDuoNzkjHA/M=","title":"PostgreSQL: narrow/wide integer types (I8, U8..U128, I128) don't round-trip.","message":"The PG renderer widens several `SqlType` integer variants — `I8`/`U8` → `smallint`,\n`I128`/`U64`/`U128` → `numeric` (`crates/squealy-postgresql/src/sql.rs:1319-1326`) — but\nintrospection has no inverse mapping: `smallint` → `I16` only (`introspect.rs:596`), and bare\n`numeric` (no typmod) → `parametric_sql_type` returns `None` → `SqlType::Raw(\"numeric\")`\n(`:669-672, 611`).\n\nSo a column modelled as `I8`/`U8`/`I128`/`U64`/`U128` is rendered, then read back as `I16` /\n`Raw(\"numeric\")`, and the diff never converges (a perpetual spurious `AlterColumn`). Because the\nwidening is lossy (many neutral types share one PG type), a faithful inverse isn't possible without\nextra encoding; options are to narrow the neutral integer vocabulary for PG, tag the rendered\ncolumn (comment/typmod) to recover the intended width, or document these as unsupported on PG.\n\nFound in the introspection round-trip audit (see ~/.claude/plans/squealy-introspection-audit.md).","files":null}]}